Removal of minerals, primarily calcium carbonate, is called as demineralization. It is commonly accomplished by acid treatment using sulphuric acid, hydrochloric acid, nitric acid, acetic acid and formic acid (Percot et al. 2003). Hydrochloric acid is the superior reagent among all these acids. Demineralization involves decomposition of calcium carbonate into calcium chloride along with the discharge of carbon dioxide as shown:2HCl+CaCO3→CaCl2+H2O+CO2↑\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
